e in 1124, and his second son Robert became the founder of the Scottish house of Bruce. — This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Brousse","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: topographic name for someone living in a scrubby area, from Old French <i>bro(u)ce</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’ (from Late Latin <i>bruscia</i>), or a habitational name from any of several places in France named Brousse. Compare   Bruce   and   Brusse  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered form <i>Bruce</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Brewis","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Briouze in Orne.","(Northumberland and Durham): topographic name or nickname from Middle English <i>breuhous</i> ‘brewery’ (literally ‘brew house’)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":95,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":104,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Grisacre Bruce was born about 1120, in Yorkshire, England. She had at least 1 son with Osbert De Babthorpe."},"et":{"